{"TopicId":188199,"ForumId":44,"TopicTitle":"Discovery of a 2nd Interstellar Object - C/2019 Q4 (Borisov)","CreatedByName":"EchoLima","CreatedById":61992,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-13T05:14:32Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"EchoLima","CreatedById":61992,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-13T05:14:32Z","Content":"\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed1695347481\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://twitter.com/tony873004/status/1172356347829964800\u0022 style=\u0022height:527px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt will be at its\u00A0perihelion around December 7 at a distance of\u00A02.07 AU.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-13T05:31:03Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIsn\u0027t any known object on hyperbolic orbit interstellar?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"mikegarrison","CreatedById":137807,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-13T07:16:46Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223671440\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188199\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221568352663\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 hour ago, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIsn\u0027t any known object on hyperbolic orbit interstellar?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWell, setting aside whether \u0022orbit\u0022 is the right word for a hyperbolic trajectory, I guess that would be so. But what objects do you think are known to be on hyperbolic trajectories?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe Wikipedia article on this object says:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nQuote\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003EThe\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_excess_velocity\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022 style=\u0022color:#0b0080;font-size:14px;\u0022 title=\u0022Hyperbolic excess velocity\u0022\u003Ehyperbolic excess velocity\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022v_{\\infty }\u0022 data-ratio=\u002266.67\u0022 style=\u0022border:0px;vertical-align:-.671ex;\u0022 width=\u002224\u0022 src=\u0022https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/26145027656115364f96e031bca0c0c11022986e\u0022\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E\u00A0of \u2248\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E30\u00A0km/s\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003Eis an important indicator that it is interstellar\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003Eas a\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022v_{\\infty }\u0022 data-ratio=\u002266.67\u0022 style=\u0022border:0px;vertical-align:-.671ex;\u0022 width=\u002224\u0022 src=\u0022https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/26145027656115364f96e031bca0c0c11022986e\u0022\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003Eunder\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E3\u00A0km/s\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;font-size:14px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003Ecan be explained by perturbations.\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI guess the point there is that if we see an object that, as best we can tell, is on a very slightly hyperbolic trajectory, we can guess it\u0027s actually from our own stellar cloud and has just been boosted a little by interactions with other objects.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWikipedia does say that an object named\u00A0C/1980 E1 (Bowell) is on a solar escape trajectory, but it is believed to have been a formerly solar comet that was boosted by Jupiter.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-09-13T07:26:20Z\u0022 title=\u002209/13/2019 07:26  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003ESeptember 13, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by mikegarrison\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-13T08:06:28Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223671476\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188199\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221568359006\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022137807\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022mikegarrison\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n47 minutes ago, mikegarrison said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut what objects do you think are known to be on hyperbolic trajectories?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAll non-periodic comets, aren\u0027t them?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"mikegarrison","CreatedById":137807,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-13T08:24:44Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI suppose it\u0027s a matter of definitions. So-called non-periodic comets come from somewhere far away, but I think the thinking is that most of them are objects that are in the outer parts of our stellar system and just get perturbed into making a visit close by the sun. They may escape, or they may come back again so long from now that nobody will ever know it was the same object.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nPart of the problem is that it\u0027s really hard to tell the difference between an orbit that is just slightly under 1.0 eccentricity and one that is just slightly over 1.0 eccentricity.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis object seems to be coming in with so much velocity that it has clearly come from outside our solar system. It has an eccentricity somewhere between 3 and 5, so it\u0027s definitely not from here.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"UmbralRaptor","CreatedById":2767,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-13T23:45:53Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223671495\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188199\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221568361988\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n15 hours ago, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAll non-periodic comets, aren\u0027t them?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThose tend to be fit with parabolas, and depending on reference frame may only have an eccentricity above 1 once you have a bunch of sig figs. For example: \u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C/2006_P1_(McNaught)\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C/2006_P1_(McNaught)\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnyway, the 3 highest eccentricities: C/1980 E1 (Bowell) at 1.0575, 1I/\u02BBOumuamua at 1.19951, and C/2019 Q4 (Borisov) at... still being determined but probably above 3.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"UmbralRaptor","CreatedById":2767,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-16T01:31:56Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nKind of a bump/update: some people determined what it would take to intercept C/2019 Q4: \u003Ca href=\u0022https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.06348\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://arxiv.org/abs/1909.06348\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnyone got a spare HLV?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"UmbralRaptor","CreatedById":2767,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-01-09T22:58:32Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMore updates:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSearching for Borisov\u0027s origins: the best guess is unlikely, so it may have been floating around for quite some time - \u003Ca href=\u0022https://arxiv.org/abs/1912.10213\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://arxiv.org/abs/1912.10213\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBorisov may have formed from an AGB star o_O - \u003Ca href=\u0022https://arxiv.org/abs/1912.12730\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://arxiv.org/abs/1912.12730\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Scotius","CreatedById":57622,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-01-10T22:15:28Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOh, to get our hands on some samples from such exotic visitor \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}